<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>Realised that while there&#39;s always new music to discover even for a longtime listener, listening to a lot of classical makes you appreciate the art of different interpretations just as much, to the point where for me personally it&#39;s the primary way I engage with the music now. I spend more time now collecting a palette of different interpretations, especially with pianists, of pieces I usually know well.</p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/opus52"> /u/opus52 </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/classicalmusic/comments/1326xpn/thought_the_more_you_listen_to_classical/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/classicalmusic/comments/1326xpn/thought_the_more_you_listen_to_classical/">[comments]</a></span>